## Discovery Insight: Hidden Housing Opportunities

Some of the most accessible housing opportunities do not appear on major real estate platforms. Instead, they emerge through smaller social channels, subletting situations, or niche communities where competition is lower and landlords may have more flexible requirements.

However, discovering these opportunities requires constant monitoring of fragmented channels and often involves uncertainty regarding trust and legitimacy.


### Discovery Insight: Response Bottleneck in Housing Platforms

While some platforms already allow users to discover available rooms or apartments, the main friction occurs after the initial contact.

Users often send dozens of messages to landlords or tenants, but response rates remain low. In many cases, users receive no reply at all, creating uncertainty and forcing them to repeat the process across multiple listings.

This creates a high-effort interaction loop where users must continuously send outreach messages without knowing whether they will receive a response.

### Discovery Insight: Uncertain Response Probability

Some housing platforms allow users to see how many people have already contacted the landlord or tenant. However, this information does not indicate whether the landlord is still actively responding.

As a result, users continue sending messages even when the probability of receiving a response may already be very low. This creates an experience where housing search feels like a game of chance rather than a structured process.

### Discovery Insight: Template Messaging Behavior

Due to the high competition and low response rates in housing platforms, users often adopt a template messaging strategy.

Instead of writing personalized messages for each listing, users create a standard message and send it to dozens of landlords or tenants in order to increase their chances of receiving a response.

This behavior reflects a system where outreach volume becomes more important than meaningful interaction.


### Discovery Insight: Landlord Segmentation

Not all landlords behave the same way in the housing market. Individual landlords who manage a single property or temporary sublets may have different incentives and flexibility compared to professional landlords or real estate agencies.

These smaller landlords may respond more personally and sometimes accept tenants with non-traditional profiles, such as freelancers or people without local employment documentation.

